# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: irrigation-automation
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:irrigation-automation/center-pivot-irrigation] Norton of Odebolt, Iowa, filed the patent for the center-pivot irrigation system.
[src:irrigation-automation/center-pivot-irrigation] The patent drawings shows multiple pairs of wheels supporting a pipe that is moved in a circle around a central pivot point.
[src:irrigation-automation/center-pivot-irrigation] The description is: Watering arrangements making use of movable installations on wheels or the like movable around a pivot center.
[src:irrigation-automation/center-pivot-irrigation] Center-pivot irrigation was invented in 1940 by the farmer Frank Zybach, who lived in Strasburg, Colorado.
[src:irrigation-automation/center-pivot-irrigation] It is recognized as an effective method to improve water distribution to fields.
[src:irrigation-automation/center-pivot-irrigation] In 1952, Zybach went into business with A.
[src:irrigation-automation/center-pivot-irrigation] Trowbridge, a friend, Ethan James Olson, from Columbus, Nebraska.
[src:irrigation-automation/center-pivot-irrigation] Trowbridge put up $25,000 (equivalent to $303,000 in 2025) and got 49% of the patent rights.
[src:irrigation-automation/center-pivot-irrigation] Zybach moved back from Colorado to Columbus, opened a shop, hired a few men, moved the height of the pipe up to 1.8 m (6 ft), and went into business.
[src:irrigation-automation/center-pivot-irrigation] In the first two years of operation, they sold only 19 systems.
[src:irrigation-automation/center-pivot-irrigation] The early designs were finicky and few farmers understood the systems.
[src:irrigation-automation/center-pivot-irrigation] Zybach kept improving his designs and focused on making his machines better, rather than attempting to sell systems with problems.
[src:irrigation-automation/center-pivot-irrigation] Zybach saw success with modified designs, which improved the systems operational efficiency.
[src:irrigation-automation/center-pivot-irrigation] In 1954, he licensed his patent to Robert Daugherty and his company, Valley Manufacturing.
[src:irrigation-automation/center-pivot-irrigation] Daugherty's engineers spent the next decade refining Zybach's innovation, making it sturdier, taller, and more reliable, and converting it from a hydraulic power system to electric drive.
[src:irrigation-automation/center-pivot-irrigation] Daugherty's company went on to grow into Valmont Industries, with Valley Irrigation being its subsidiary.
[src:irrigation-automation/center-pivot-irrigation] Center-pivot irrigation is a form of overhead sprinkler irrigation consisting of several segments of pipe (usually galvanized steel or aluminum) with sprinklers positioned along their length, joined together and supported by trusses, and mounted on wheeled towers.
[src:irrigation-automation/center-pivot-irrigation] The machine moves in a circular pattern and is fed with water from the pivot point at the center of the circle.
[src:irrigation-automation/center-pivot-irrigation] For a center pivot to be used, the terrain needs to be reasonably flat; but one major advantage of center pivots over alternative systems that use gravity flow is the ability to function in undulating country.
[src:irrigation-automation/center-pivot-irrigation] This advantage has resulted in increased irrigated land area and water use in some areas.
[src:irrigation-automation/center-pivot-irrigation] The system is used in parts of the United States, Australia, New Zealand, Brazil, and in desert areas such as the Sahara and the Middle East.
[src:irrigation-automation/center-pivot-irrigation] Center pivots are typically less than 500 meters (1,600 ft) in length (circle radius), with the most common size being the standard 400-meter (1⁄4 mi) machine, which covers about 50 hectares (125 acres) of land.
[src:irrigation-automation/center-pivot-irrigation] Originally, most center pivots were water-powered.
[src:irrigation-automation/center-pivot-irrigation] These were replaced by hydraulic systems and electric motor-driven systems, usually driven by a motor mounted at each tower.
[src:irrigation-automation/center-pivot-irrigation] The outside set of wheels sets the pace for the rotation.
[src:irrigation-automation/center-pivot-irrigation] The inner sets of wheels are mounted at hubs between two segments and use angle sensors (microswitches) to detect when the bend at the joint exceeds a certain threshold.
[src:irrigation-automation/center-pivot-irrigation] When the angle is too large, the wheels rotate to keep the segments aligned.
[src:irrigation-automation/center-pivot-irrigation] Typical periods for a full rotation include three days; while other sources have the outer edge of the structure moving at 2 to 3 m (6.6 to 9.8 ft) per minute, which would equate to 14 to 21 hours for one full rotation of a 400-meter-radius (1⁄4 mi) system.
[src:irrigation-automation/center-pivot-irrigation] To achieve uniform application, center pivots require a variable emitter flow rate across the radius of the machine.
[src:irrigation-automation/center-pivot-irrigation] Since the outer-most spans (or towers) travel farther in a given time period than the innermost spans, nozzle sizes are smallest at the inner spans and increase with distance from the pivot point.
[src:irrigation-automation/center-pivot-irrigation] Most center-pivot systems now have drops hanging from a U-shaped pipe called a *gooseneck* attached at the top of the pipe with sprinkler heads that are positioned a few feet (at most) above the crop, thus limiting evaporative losses and wind drift.
[src:irrigation-automation/center-pivot-irrigation] There are many different nozzle configurations available including static plate, moving plate and part circle.
[src:irrigation-automation/center-pivot-irrigation] Pressure regulators are typically installed upstream of each nozzle to ensure each is operating at the correct design pressure.
[src:irrigation-automation/center-pivot-irrigation] Drops can also be used with drag hoses or bubblers that deposit the water directly on the ground between crops.
[src:irrigation-automation/center-pivot-irrigation] This type of system is known as LEPA (Low Energy Precision Application) and is often associated with the construction of small dams along the furrow length (termed furrow diking/dyking).
[src:irrigation-automation/center-pivot-irrigation] Crops may be planted either in straight rows or in circles to conform to the travel of the irrigation system.
[src:irrigation-automation/center-pivot-irrigation] Irrigation equipment can also be configured to move in a straight line, where it is termed a *lateral move*, *linear move*, *wheel move* or *side-roll* irrigation system.
[src:irrigation-automation/center-pivot-irrigation] In these systems the water is supplied by an irrigation channel running the length of the field.
[src:irrigation-automation/center-pivot-irrigation] The channel is positioned either at one side or in a line through the center.
[src:irrigation-automation/center-pivot-irrigation] The motor and pump equipment are mounted on a cart by the supply channel.
[src:irrigation-automation/center-pivot-irrigation] Farmers might choose lateral-move irrigation to keep existing rectangular fields.
[src:irrigation-automation/center-pivot-irrigation] This can help them convert from furrow irrigation.
[src:irrigation-automation/center-pivot-irrigation] Lateral-move irrigation is far less common, relies on more complex guidance systems, and requires additional management compared to center pivot irrigation.
[src:irrigation-automation/center-pivot-irrigation] Lateral-move irrigation is common in Australia.
[src:irrigation-automation/center-pivot-irrigation] There, systems are usually between 500 and 1,000 meters long.
[src:irrigation-automation/center-pivot-irrigation] Center-pivot irrigation uses less labor than many other surface irrigation methods, such as furrow irrigation.
[src:irrigation-automation/center-pivot-irrigation] It also has lower labor costs than ground-irrigation techniques that require digging of channels.
[src:irrigation-automation/center-pivot-irrigation] Also, center-pivot irrigation can reduce the amount of soil tillage.
[src:irrigation-automation/center-pivot-irrigation] Therefore, it helps reduce water runoff and soil erosion that can occur with ground irrigation.
[src:irrigation-automation/center-pivot-irrigation] Less tillage also encourages more organic materials and crop residue to decompose back into the soil.
[src:irrigation-automation/center-pivot-irrigation] In the United States early settlers of the semiarid High Plains were plagued by crop failures due to cycles of drought, culminating in the disastrous Dust Bowl of the 1930s.
[src:irrigation-automation/center-pivot-irrigation] Only after World War II when center pivot irrigation became available did the land mass of the High Plains aquifer system transform into one of the most agriculturally productive regions in the world.
[src:irrigation-automation/center-pivot-irrigation] Groundwater levels decrease when the rate of extraction by irrigation exceeds the rate of recharge.
[src:irrigation-automation/center-pivot-irrigation] By 2013 it was shown that, counterintuitively, as the water consumption efficiency of center-pivot irrigation improved over the years, farmers planted more intensively, irrigated more land, and grew thirstier crops.
[src:irrigation-automation/center-pivot-irrigation] This is an example of the Jevons paradox.
[src:irrigation-automation/center-pivot-irrigation] In parts of the United States, sixty years of the profitable business of intensive farming using huge center-pivot irrigators has emptied parts of the Ogallala Aquifer (also known as the High Plains Aquifer).
[src:irrigation-automation/center-pivot-irrigation] One of the world's largest aquifers, it covers an area of approximately 450,000 km2 (170,000 sq mi) in portions of the eight states of South Dakota, Nebraska, Wyoming, Colorado, Kansas, Oklahoma, New Mexico, and Texas, beneath the Great Plains in the United States.
[src:irrigation-automation/center-pivot-irrigation] The total water extraction from center-pivot irrigation in the area is estimated to be about 5.42 million acre-feet per year (6.69 km3/a).
[src:irrigation-automation/center-pivot-irrigation] With the use of center-pivot irrigation, nearly 1.2 million hectares (3 million acres) of land were irrigated in Kansas alone.
[src:irrigation-automation/center-pivot-irrigation] At some places, during maximum extraction, the water table dropped more than 1.5 m (5 ft) per year.
[src:irrigation-automation/center-pivot-irrigation] In extreme cases, wells had to be greatly deepened to reach the steadily falling water table.
[src:irrigation-automation/center-pivot-irrigation] In some places in the Texas Panhandle, the water table has been drained (dewatered).
[src:irrigation-automation/center-pivot-irrigation] "Vast stretches of Texas farmland lying over the aquifer no longer support irrigation.
[src:irrigation-automation/center-pivot-irrigation] In west-central Kansas, up to a fifth of the irrigated farmland along a 100-mile [160 km] swath of the aquifer has already gone dry." It would take hundreds to thousands of years of rainfall to replace the groundwater in the dried up aquifer.
[src:irrigation-automation/center-pivot-irrigation] In the 21st century, recognition of the significance of the High Plains Aquifer has led to increased coverage from regional and international journalists.
[src:irrigation-automation/center-pivot-irrigation] A May 2013 *New York Times* article "Wells dry, fertile plains turn to dust" recounts the relentless decline of parts of the High Plains Aquifer System.
[src:irrigation-automation/center-pivot-irrigation] A new generation chose high-risk, high-reward crops such as irrigated corn or peanuts, which require large quantities of groundwater, fertilizer and chemicals.
[src:irrigation-automation/center-pivot-irrigation] The new family farm corporations turned many pastures into new cropland and were more interested in rising land prices than water conservation.
[src:irrigation-automation/drip-irrigation] As of 2023, 3% of the world's farmers use drip irrigation.
[src:irrigation-automation/drip-irrigation] Primitive drip irrigation has been used since ancient times.
[src:irrigation-automation/drip-irrigation] *Fan Shengzhi shu*, written in China during the first century BCE, describes the use of buried, unglazed clay pots filled with water, sometimes referred to as Ollas, as a means of irrigation.
[src:irrigation-automation/drip-irrigation] Modern drip irrigation began its development in Germany in 1860 when researchers began experimenting with subsurface irrigation using clay pipe to create combination irrigation and drainage systems.
[src:irrigation-automation/drip-irrigation] The research was later expanded in the 1920s to include the application of perforated pipe systems.
[src:irrigation-automation/drip-irrigation] The usage of plastic to hold and distribute water in drip irrigation was later developed in Australia by Hannis Thill.
[src:irrigation-automation/drip-irrigation] Usage of a plastic emitter in drip irrigation was developed in Israel by Simcha Blass and his son Yeshayahu.
[src:irrigation-automation/drip-irrigation] Instead of releasing water through tiny holes easily blocked by tiny particles, water was released through larger and longer passageways by using friction to slow water inside a plastic emitter.
[src:irrigation-automation/drip-irrigation] The first experimental system of this type was established in 1959 by Blass, who partnered later in 1964 with Kibbutz Hatzerim to create an irrigation company called Netafim.
[src:irrigation-automation/drip-irrigation] Together, they developed and patented the first practical surface drip irrigation emitter.
[src:irrigation-automation/drip-irrigation] Modern drip irrigation was invented in Israel in the 1960s.
[src:irrigation-automation/drip-irrigation] Such irrigation also improved the efficiency of fertilizer use, as well as water.
[src:irrigation-automation/drip-irrigation] The introduction of this technology was revolutionary according to *The Times of Israel*, and could save 70% of water usage in the growth of rice.
[src:irrigation-automation/drip-irrigation] Goldberg and Shmueli (1970) developed a significant improvement: "in the Arava desert in southern Israel, [Shmueli] demonstrated that a trickle-irrigation system installed on the soil surface worked exceptionally well in producing vegetable crops, even with saline or salt water (Elfving, 1989).
[src:irrigation-automation/drip-irrigation] The system...was responsible for the greening of formerly unproductive environment".
[src:irrigation-automation/drip-irrigation] Replacing sub-surface system with on surface system solved the disadvantage of clogging the subsurface system.
[src:irrigation-automation/drip-irrigation] Their improvement prevailed: "Drip irrigation is presently the most efficient means to apply water to crops (Pathak et al.
[src:irrigation-automation/drip-irrigation] There are two variations of the technology: surface, and subsurface.
[src:irrigation-automation/drip-irrigation] The most common is surface drip irrigation, first developed in Israel (Goldberg and Shmueli 1970)...
[src:irrigation-automation/drip-irrigation] Due to the need to improve irrigation efficiency, as a measure toward sustainable use of water resources, there is wide interest in drip irrigation (Scanlon et al.
[src:irrigation-automation/drip-irrigation] Netafim developed technology to specifically water rice.
[src:irrigation-automation/drip-irrigation] Rice paddies produce 10% of global methane emissions, the equivalent of 400 million cars.
[src:irrigation-automation/drip-irrigation] This technology was first introduced in Italy, Turkey, and India.
[src:irrigation-automation/drip-irrigation] Agritech firm N-Drip developed smart drip irrigation for rice paddies.
[src:irrigation-automation/drip-irrigation] In the TOI article it was reported that N-Drip system led to yield increases of up to 33%, fertilizer reduction of 50%, a drop in greenhouse gases like carbon and methane from 50% to 85%, as well as water savings of 50%.
[src:irrigation-automation/drip-irrigation] In the United States, the first drip tape, called *Dew Hose*, was developed by Richard Chapin and Jaime Leal-Diaz of Chapin Watermatics in the early 1960s.
[src:irrigation-automation/drip-irrigation] The evolution of drip tape which made large-scale adoption and use possible was the introduction of T-Tape in 1987 by Plastro Irrigation, that had the first slit outlet and a laminar flow track which later evolved into a turbulent flow regulating flow track.
[src:irrigation-automation/drip-irrigation] Chapin Watermatics was acquired by Jain Irrigation in 2006 and is housed under its US subsidiary Jain Irrigation Inc, USA.
[src:irrigation-automation/drip-irrigation] First introduced in California in the late 1960s, only 5% of irrigated land used this system by 1988.
[src:irrigation-automation/drip-irrigation] However, by 2010, 40% of irrigated land in California used this system.
[src:irrigation-automation/drip-irrigation] A trickle ring is a circular device which evenly distributes water around the base of a tree or shrub.
[src:irrigation-automation/drip-irrigation] Connected to a water supply by a garden hose or tubing adapter fitting, trickle rings may be integrated into an irrigation network which waters many plants at the same time.
[src:irrigation-automation/drip-irrigation] By regulating the flow of water through the trickle ring, soil can be saturated at a rate which conserves water by minimizing wasteful surface runoff and losses due to evaporation.
[src:irrigation-automation/drip-irrigation] Modern drip irrigation has arguably become the world's most valued innovation in agriculture since the invention in the 1930s of the impact sprinkler, which offered the first practical alternative to surface irrigation.
[src:irrigation-automation/drip-irrigation] Careful study of all the relevant factors like land topography, soil, water, crop and agro-climatic conditions are needed to determine the most suitable drip irrigation system and components to be used in a specific installation.
[src:irrigation-automation/drip-irrigation] Drip irrigation may also use devices called micro-spray heads, which spray water in a small area, instead of dripping emitters.
[src:irrigation-automation/drip-irrigation] These are generally used on tree and vine crops with wider root zones.
[src:irrigation-automation/drip-irrigation] Subsurface drip irrigation (SDI) uses permanently or temporarily buried dripperline or drip tape located at or below the plant roots.
[src:irrigation-automation/drip-irrigation] It is becoming popular for row crop irrigation, especially in areas where water supplies are limited, or recycled water is used for irrigation.
[src:irrigation-automation/drip-irrigation] As of 2012, China and India were the fastest expanding countries in the field of drip- or other micro-irrigation, while worldwide well over ten million hectares used these technologies.
[src:irrigation-automation/drip-irrigation] Still, this amounted to less than 4 percent of the world's irrigated land.
[src:irrigation-automation/drip-irrigation] That year, Israel's Netafim was the global market leader (a position it maintained in 2018), with India's Jain Irrigation being the second-biggest micro-irrigation company.
[src:irrigation-automation/drip-irrigation] In 2017 Rivulis bought Eurodrip and became the world's second largest irrigation systems manufacturer.
[src:irrigation-automation/drip-irrigation] In drip irrigation systems, pump and valves may be manually or automatically operated by a smart controller.
[src:irrigation-automation/drip-irrigation] Most large drip irrigation systems employ some type of filter to prevent clogging of the small emitter flow path by small waterborne particles.
[src:irrigation-automation/drip-irrigation] New technologies are now being offered that minimize clogging.
[src:irrigation-automation/drip-irrigation] Some residential systems are installed without additional filters since potable water is already filtered at the water treatment plant.
[src:irrigation-automation/drip-irrigation] Virtually all drip irrigation equipment manufacturers recommend that filters be employed and generally will not honor warranties unless this is done.
[src:irrigation-automation/drip-irrigation] Last line filters just before the final delivery pipe are strongly recommended in addition to any other filtration system due to fine particle settlement and accidental insertion of particles in the intermediate lines.
[src:irrigation-automation/drip-irrigation] Drip and subsurface drip irrigation is used almost exclusively when using recycled municipal wastewater.
[src:irrigation-automation/drip-irrigation] Regulations typically do not permit spraying water through the air that has not been fully treated to potable water standards.
[src:irrigation-automation/drip-irrigation] Because of the way the water is applied in a drip system, traditional surface applications of timed-release fertilizer are sometimes ineffective, so drip systems often mix liquid fertilizer with the irrigation water.
[src:irrigation-automation/drip-irrigation] This is called fertigation; fertigation and chemigation (application of pesticides and other chemicals to periodically clean out the system, such as chlorine or sulfuric acid) use chemical injectors such as diaphragm pumps, piston pumps, or aspirators.
[src:irrigation-automation/drip-irrigation] The chemicals may be added constantly whenever the system is irrigating or at intervals.
[src:irrigation-automation/drip-irrigation] Fertilizer savings of up to 95% are being reported from recent university field tests using drip fertigation and slow water delivery as compared to timed-release and irrigation by micro spray heads.
[src:irrigation-automation/drip-irrigation] Properly designed, installed, and managed, drip irrigation may help achieve water conservation by reducing evaporation and deep drainage when compared to other types of irrigation such as flood or overhead sprinklers since water can be more precisely applied to the plant roots.
[src:irrigation-automation/drip-irrigation] In addition, drip can eliminate many diseases that are spread through water contact with the foliage.
[src:irrigation-automation/drip-irrigation] Finally, in regions where water supplies are severely limited, there may be no actual water savings, but rather simply an increase in production while using the same amount of water as before.
[src:irrigation-automation/drip-irrigation] In very arid regions or on sandy soils, the preferred method is to apply the irrigation water as slowly as possible.
[src:irrigation-automation/drip-irrigation] Pulsed irrigation is sometimes used to decrease the amount of water delivered to the plant at any one time, thus reducing runoff or deep percolation.
[src:irrigation-automation/drip-irrigation] Pulsed systems are typically expensive and require extensive maintenance.
[src:irrigation-automation/drip-irrigation] Therefore, the latest efforts by emitter manufacturers are focused on developing new technologies that deliver irrigation water at ultra-low flow rates, i.e. less than 1.0 L (2.1 US pints; 1.8 imperial pints) per hour.
[src:irrigation-automation/drip-irrigation] Slow-and-even delivery further improves water use efficiency without incurring the expense and complexity of pulsed delivery equipment.
[src:irrigation-automation/drip-irrigation] An emitting pipe is a type of drip irrigation tubing with emitters pre-installed at the factory with specific distance and flow per hour as per crop distance.
[src:irrigation-automation/drip-irrigation] An emitter restricts water flow passage through it, thus creating head loss required (to the extent of atmospheric pressure) to emit water in the form of droplets.
[src:irrigation-automation/drip-irrigation] This head loss is achieved by friction/turbulence within the emitter.
[src:irrigation-automation/drip-irrigation] Drip tape is a type of thin-walled dripper line used in drip irrigation.
[src:irrigation-automation/drip-irrigation] The first drip tape was known as "Dew Hose".
[src:irrigation-automation/drip-irrigation] Drip tape duct tape is made of polyethylene and sold flat on reels.
[src:irrigation-automation/drip-irrigation] The wall thickness typically ranges from 0.1 to 0.6 mm (4 to 25 mils).
[src:irrigation-automation/drip-irrigation] Thicker-walled tapes are commonly used for permanent subsurface drip irrigation, and thinner-walled tapes for temporary throw-away systems in high-value crops.
[src:irrigation-automation/drip-irrigation] Water exits from tape through emitters or drippers.
[src:irrigation-automation/drip-irrigation] The typical emitter spacing ranges from 150 to 610 mm (6 to 24 inches).
[src:irrigation-automation/drip-irrigation] In some products, the emitters are manufactured simultaneously with the tape and formed as part of the product.
[src:irrigation-automation/drip-irrigation] In others, the emitters are manufactured separately and installed during production.
[src:irrigation-automation/drip-irrigation] Some products are not tape but a thin-walled dripper line, but in popular parlance, both types of products are called tapes.
[src:irrigation-automation/drip-irrigation] Typical tape diameters are 16 mm (5⁄8 in), 22 mm (7⁄8 in), and 35 mm (1+3⁄8 in), with the larger diameters more commonly used on permanent installations with longer runs.
[src:irrigation-automation/drip-irrigation] Drip tape is a recyclable material and can be recycled into viable plastic resins for reuse in the plastics manufacturing industry.
[src:irrigation-automation/drip-irrigation] Drip irrigation is used in farms, commercial greenhouses, and residential gardens.
[src:irrigation-automation/drip-irrigation] Drip irrigation is adopted extensively in areas of acute water scarcity and especially for crops and trees such as coconuts, containerized landscape trees, grapes, bananas, ber, eggplant, citrus, strawberries, sugarcane, cotton, maize, and tomatoes.
[src:irrigation-automation/drip-irrigation] Drip irrigation kits for home gardens are increasingly popular for homeowners and consist of a timer, hose, and emitter.
[src:irrigation-automation/drip-irrigation] Hoses that are 4 mm (0.16 in) in diameter are used to irrigate flower pots.
[src:irrigation-automation/evapotranspiration] Evapotranspiration is a combination of evaporation and transpiration, measured in order to better understand crop water requirements, irrigation scheduling, and watershed management.
[src:irrigation-automation/evapotranspiration] Evapotranspiration is typically measured in millimeters of water (i.e. volume of water moved per unit area of the Earth's surface) in a set unit of time.
[src:irrigation-automation/evapotranspiration] Globally, it is estimated that on average between three-fifths and three-quarters of land precipitation is returned to the atmosphere via evapotranspiration.
[src:irrigation-automation/evapotranspiration] Levels of evapotranspiration in a given area are primarily controlled by three factors: Firstly, the amount of water present which includes the amount of available water in both the soil and in larger bodies of water.
[src:irrigation-automation/evapotranspiration] Regarding the second factor (energy and heat): climate change has increased global temperatures (see instrumental temperature record).
[src:irrigation-automation/evapotranspiration] This global warming has increased evapotranspiration over land.
[src:irrigation-automation/evapotranspiration] The increased evapotranspiration is one of the effects of climate change on the water cycle.
[src:irrigation-automation/evapotranspiration] Vegetation type impacts levels of evapotranspiration.
[src:irrigation-automation/evapotranspiration] For example, herbaceous plants generally transpire less than woody plants, because they usually have less extensive foliage.
[src:irrigation-automation/evapotranspiration] Also, plants with deep reaching roots can transpire water more constantly, because those roots can pull more water into the plant and leaves.
[src:irrigation-automation/evapotranspiration] Another example is that conifer forests tend to have higher rates of evapotranspiration than deciduous broadleaf forests, particularly in the dormant winter and early spring seasons, because they are evergreen.
[src:irrigation-automation/evapotranspiration] With crop vegetation being widespread, evapotranspiration may also be called "**corn sweat**".
[src:irrigation-automation/evapotranspiration] Transpiration is a larger component of evapotranspiration (relative to evaporation) in vegetation-abundant areas.
[src:irrigation-automation/evapotranspiration] As a result, denser vegetation, like forests, may increase evapotranspiration and reduce water yield.
[src:irrigation-automation/evapotranspiration] Vegetation coverage also leads to a reduction in the overall surface temperature and the way solar energy effects evapotranspiration rates.
[src:irrigation-automation/evapotranspiration] Through this, heat transfer can be facilitated faster between the atmosphere and the surface increasing evaporation rates.
[src:irrigation-automation/evapotranspiration] The density of vegetation coverage can control different environmental conditions of varying ecosystems and the way that water moves through the system.
[src:irrigation-automation/evapotranspiration] Different vegetation coverages control the conditions on transpiration, but the evapotranspiration process will vary from plant-to-plant base on individual features of the plant.
[src:irrigation-automation/evapotranspiration] Two exceptions to this are cloud forests and rainforests.
[src:irrigation-automation/evapotranspiration] In cloud forests, trees collect the liquid water in fog or low clouds onto their surface, which eventually drips down to the ground.
[src:irrigation-automation/evapotranspiration] These trees still contribute to evapotranspiration, but often collect more water than they evaporate or transpire.
[src:irrigation-automation/evapotranspiration] In rainforests, water yield is increased (compared to cleared, unforested land in the same climatic zone) as evapotranspiration increases humidity within the forest (a portion of which condenses and returns quickly as precipitation experienced at ground level as rain).
[src:irrigation-automation/evapotranspiration] The density of the vegetation blocks sunlight and reduces temperatures at ground level (thereby reducing losses due to surface evaporation), and reduces wind speeds (thereby reducing the loss of airborne moisture).
[src:irrigation-automation/evapotranspiration] The combined effect results in increased surface stream flows and a higher ground water table whilst the rainforest is preserved.
[src:irrigation-automation/evapotranspiration] Clearing of rainforests frequently leads to desertification as ground level temperatures and wind speeds increase, vegetation cover is lost or intentionally destroyed by clearing and burning, soil moisture is reduced by wind, and soils are easily eroded by high wind and rainfall events.
[src:irrigation-automation/evapotranspiration] Areas that are highly irrigated have a higher amount of moisture that is consistent in the soil.
[src:irrigation-automation/evapotranspiration] Moisture content within the soil effects total evapotranspiration.
[src:irrigation-automation/evapotranspiration] Areas with lower moisture levels in the soil result in lower evapotranspiration interaction and will increase the surface temperature of the soil.
[src:irrigation-automation/evapotranspiration] Areas with higher moisture levels will have more effective evapotranspiration and decrease the surface temperature of the soil.An exception is areas with high water tables, where capillary action can cause water from the groundwater to rise through the soil matrix back to the surface.
[src:irrigation-automation/evapotranspiration] If potential evapotranspiration is greater than the actual precipitation, then soil will dry out until conditions stabilize, unless irrigation is used.
[src:irrigation-automation/evapotranspiration] More information about how evapotranspiration effects overall crop production will lead to the ability to better produce higher quality crops and increase our ability to sustainably irrigate our fields efficiently in large scale agricultural operations.
[src:irrigation-automation/evapotranspiration] It is shown that where irrigation systems are being implemented, fields and crops are seeing increased levels of evapotranspiration.
[src:irrigation-automation/evapotranspiration] While on the contrary in places where irrigation methods are not used lower evapotranspiration levels are seen.
[src:irrigation-automation/evapotranspiration] As the agriculture industry continues to evolve, new agricultural technologies and fertilizers are leading to an increase in evapotranspiration rates.
[src:irrigation-automation/evapotranspiration] Evapotranspiration can be measured directly with a weighing or pan lysimeter.
[src:irrigation-automation/evapotranspiration] A lysimeter continuously measures the weight of a plant and associated soil, and any water added by precipitation or irrigation.
[src:irrigation-automation/evapotranspiration] The change in storage of water in the soil is then modeled by measuring the change in weight.
[src:irrigation-automation/evapotranspiration] When used properly, this allows for precise measurement of evapotranspiration over small areas.
[src:irrigation-automation/evapotranspiration] Because atmospheric vapor flux is difficult or time-consuming to measure directly, evapotranspiration is typically estimated by one of several different methods that do not rely on direct measurement.
[src:irrigation-automation/evapotranspiration] Evapotranspiration may be estimated by evaluating the water balance equation for a given area:.
[src:irrigation-automation/evapotranspiration] In the equation, the change in water stored within the basin (*ΔS*) is related to precipitation (*P*) (water going into the basin), and evapotranspiration (*ET*), streamflow (*Q*), and groundwater recharge (*D*) (water leaving the basin).
[src:irrigation-automation/evapotranspiration] A second methodology for estimation is by calculating the energy balance.
[src:irrigation-automation/evapotranspiration] where *λE* is the energy needed to change the phase of water from liquid to gas, *Rn* is the net radiation, *G* is the soil heat flux and *H* is the sensible heat flux.
[src:irrigation-automation/evapotranspiration] Using instruments like a scintillometer, soil heat flux plates or radiation meters, the components of the energy balance can be calculated and the energy available for actual evapotranspiration can be solved.
[src:irrigation-automation/evapotranspiration] The SEBAL and METRIC algorithms solve for the energy balance at the Earth's surface using satellite imagery.
[src:irrigation-automation/evapotranspiration] This allows for both actual and potential evapotranspiration to be calculated on a pixel-by-pixel basis.
[src:irrigation-automation/evapotranspiration] Evapotranspiration is a key indicator for water management and irrigation performance.
[src:irrigation-automation/evapotranspiration] SEBAL and METRIC can map these key indicators in time and space, for days, weeks or years.
[src:irrigation-automation/evapotranspiration] Given meteorological data like wind, temperature, and humidity, reference ET can be calculated.
[src:irrigation-automation/evapotranspiration] The most general and widely used equation for calculating reference ET is the Penman equation.
[src:irrigation-automation/evapotranspiration] The Penman–Monteith variation is recommended by the Food and Agriculture Organization and the American Society of Civil Engineers.
[src:irrigation-automation/evapotranspiration] The simpler Blaney–Criddle equation was popular in the Western United States for many years but it is not as accurate in wet regions with higher humidity.
[src:irrigation-automation/evapotranspiration] Other equations for estimating evapotranspiration from meteorological data include the Makkink equation, which is simple but must be calibrated to a specific location, and the Hargreaves equations.
[src:irrigation-automation/evapotranspiration] To convert the reference evapotranspiration to the actual crop evapotranspiration, a crop coefficient and a stress coefficient must be used.
[src:irrigation-automation/evapotranspiration] Potential evapotranspiration (PET) or potential evaporation (PE) is the amount of water that would be evaporated and transpired by a specific crop, soil or ecosystem if there was sufficient water available.
[src:irrigation-automation/evapotranspiration] It is a reflection of the energy available to evaporate or transpire water, and of the wind available to transport the water vapor from the ground up into the lower atmosphere and away from the initial location.
[src:irrigation-automation/evapotranspiration] Potential evapotranspiration is expressed in terms of a depth of water or soil moisture percentage.
[src:irrigation-automation/evapotranspiration] If the actual evapotranspiration (AET) is considered the net result of atmospheric demand for moisture from a surface and the ability of the surface to supply moisture, then PET is a measure of the demand side (also called *evaporative demand*).
[src:irrigation-automation/evapotranspiration] Surface and air temperatures, insolation, and wind all affect this.
[src:irrigation-automation/evapotranspiration] A dryland is a place where annual potential evaporation exceeds annual precipitation.
[src:irrigation-automation/evapotranspiration] Often a value for the potential evapotranspiration is calculated at a nearby climatic station on a reference surface, conventionally on land dominated by short grass (though this may differ from station to station).
[src:irrigation-automation/evapotranspiration] This value is called the reference evapotranspiration (ET0).
[src:irrigation-automation/evapotranspiration] Actual evapotranspiration is said to equal potential evapotranspiration when there is ample water present.
[src:irrigation-automation/evapotranspiration] Evapotranspiration can never be greater than potential evapotranspiration, but can be lower if there is not enough water to be evaporated or plants are unable to transpire maturely and readily.
[src:irrigation-automation/evapotranspiration] Some US states utilize a full cover alfalfa reference crop that is 0.5 m (1.6 ft) in height, rather than the general short green grass reference, due to the higher value of ET from the alfalfa reference.
[src:irrigation-automation/evapotranspiration] Potential evapotranspiration is higher in the summer, on clearer and less cloudy days, and closer to the equator, because of the higher levels of solar radiation that provides the energy (heat) for evaporation.
[src:irrigation-automation/evapotranspiration] Potential evapotranspiration is also higher on windy days because the evaporated moisture can be quickly moved from the ground or plant surface before it precipitates, allowing more evaporation to fill its place.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] Several irrigation methods differ in how water is supplied to plants.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] Surface irrigation, also known as gravity irrigation, is the oldest form of irrigation and has been in use for thousands of years.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] In sprinkler irrigation, water is piped to one or more central locations within the field and distributed by overhead high-pressure water devices.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] Micro-irrigation is a system that distributes water under low pressure through a piped network and applies it as a small discharge to each plant.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] Micro-irrigation uses less pressure and water flow than sprinkler irrigation.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] Drip irrigation delivers water directly to the root zone of plants.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] Subirrigation has been used in field crops in areas with high water tables for many years.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] It involves artificially raising the water table to moisten the soil below the root zone of plants.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] Irrigation water can come from groundwater (extracted from springs or by using wells), from surface water (withdrawn from rivers, lakes or reservoirs) or from non-conventional sources like treated wastewater, desalinated water, drainage water, or fog collection.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] Irrigation can be supplementary to rainfall, which is common in many parts of the world as rainfed agriculture, or it can be full irrigation, where crops rarely rely on any contribution from rainfall.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] Full irrigation is less common and occurs only in arid landscapes with very low rainfall or when crops are grown in semi-arid areas outside the rainy season.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] The environmental effects of irrigation relate to the changes in quantity and quality of soil and water as a result of irrigation and the subsequent effects on natural and social conditions in river basins and downstream of an irrigation scheme.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] The effects stem from altered hydrological conditions resulting from the installation and operation of the irrigation scheme.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] Amongst these problems is the depletion of underground aquifers through overdrafting.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] Soil can be over-irrigated due to poor distribution uniformity or management wastes water, chemicals, and may lead to water pollution.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] Over-irrigation can cause deep drainage from rising water tables, which can lead to irrigation salinity problems, requiring watertable control through some form of subsurface land drainage.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] The world’s total irrigated land area more than doubled between 1964 and 2023 and by 2023, 23% of all croplands were equipped for irrigation.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] In 2025 irrigated croplands produce 48% of all crops in value terms, indicating that irrigated land is 3.2 times more productive than rainfed land in value terms.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] On average, the yield of irrigated land is 76% higher than that of rain fed land.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] The global land area equipped for irrigation reached 355 million ha in 2023, an increase of 23% from the 289 million ha of 2000 and more than twice the land area equipped for irrigation in the1960s.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] China and India also have the largest net gains in equipped area between 2000 and 2023 (+21 million ha for China and +15 million ha for India).
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] In 2000, the total fertile land was 2,788,000 km2 (689 million acres), and it was equipped with irrigation infrastructure worldwide.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] Roughly 68% of this area is in Asia, 17% in the Americas, 9% in Europe, 5% in Africa, and 1% in Oceania.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] Smaller irrigation areas are spread across almost all populated parts of the world.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] By 2012, the area of irrigated land had increased to an estimated total of 3,242,917 km2 (801 million acres), which is nearly the size of India.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] The irrigation of 20% of farming land accounts for the production of 40% of food production.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] The scale of irrigation increased dramatically over the 20th century.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] In 1800, 8 million hectares globally were irrigated; in 1950, 94 million; and in 1990, 235 million.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] By 1990, 30% of the global food production came from irrigated land.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] Irrigation techniques across the globe include canals redirecting surface water, groundwater pumping, and diverting water from dams.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] National governments lead most irrigation schemes within their borders, but private investors and other nations, especially the United States, China, and European countries like the United Kingdom, also fund and organize some schemes within other nations.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] By 2021, the global land area equipped for irrigation reached 352 million ha, an increase of 22% from the 289 million ha in 2000 and more than twice the land area equipped for irrigation in the 1960s.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] The vast majority is located in Asia (70%), where irrigation was a key component of the green revolution; the Americas account for 16%, and Europe for 8% of the world total.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] India (76 million ha) and China (75 million ha) have the largest irrigated area, far ahead of the United States of America (27 million ha).
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] China and India also had the largest net gains in equipped area between 2000 and 2020 (+21 million ha in China and +15 million ha in India).
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] All regions saw increases in irrigated area, with Africa growing the fastest (+29%), followed by Asia (+25%), Oceania (+24%), the Americas (+19%), and Europe (+2%).
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] Irrigation enables the production of more crops, especially commodity crops in areas that otherwise could not support them.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] Countries frequently invested in irrigation to increase wheat, rice, or cotton production, often with the overarching goal of increasing self-sufficiency.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] While floodwater harvesting is an accepted irrigation method, rainwater harvesting is usually not considered a form of irrigation.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] Rainwater harvesting is the collection of runoff water from roofs or unused land and its concentration.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] Irrigation with recycled municipal wastewater can also serve to fertilize plants if it contains nutrients, such as nitrogen, phosphorus and potassium.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] There are benefits of using recycled water for irrigation, including the lower cost compared to some other sources and consistency of supply regardless of season, climatic conditions and associated water restrictions.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] When reclaimed water is used for irrigation in agriculture, the nutrient (nitrogen and phosphorus) content of the treated wastewater has the benefit of acting as a fertilizer.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] This can make the reuse of excreta contained in sewage attractive.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] The irrigation water can be used in different ways on different crops, such as for food crops to be eaten raw or for crops which are intended for human consumption to be eaten raw or unprocessed.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] For processed food crops: crops which are intended for human consumption not to be eaten raw but after food processing (i.e. cooked, industrially processed).
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] It can also be used on crops which are not intended for human consumption (e.g. pastures, forage, fiber, ornamental, seed, forest and turf crops).
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] In developing countries, agriculture is increasingly using untreated municipal wastewater for irrigation – often in an unsafe manner.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] Cities provide lucrative markets for fresh produce, so they are attractive to farmers.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] However, because agriculture has to compete for increasingly scarce water resources with industry and municipal users, there is often no alternative for farmers but to use water polluted with urban waste directly to water their crops.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] There can be significant health hazards related to using untreated wastewater in agriculture.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] Municipal wastewater can contain a mixture of chemical and biological pollutants.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] In low-income countries, there are often high levels of pathogens from excreta.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] In emerging nations, where industrial development is outpacing environmental regulation, there are increasing risks from inorganic and organic chemicals.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] The World Health Organization developed guidelines for safe use of wastewater in 2006, advocating a 'multiple-barrier' approach wastewater use, for example by encouraging farmers to adopt various risk-reducing behaviors.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] Drawbacks or risks often mentioned include the content of potentially harmful substances such as bacteria, heavy metals, or organic pollutants (including pharmaceuticals, personal care products and pesticides).
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] Irrigation with wastewater can have both positive and negative effects on soil and plants, depending on the composition of the wastewater and on the soil or plant characteristics.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] Irrigation water can also come from non-conventional sources like treated wastewater, desalinated water, drainage water, or fog collection.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] In countries where humid air sweeps through at night, water can be obtained by condensation onto cold surfaces.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] This is practiced in the vineyards at Lanzarote using stones to condense water.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] Fog collectors are also made of canvas or foil sheets.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] Using condensate from air conditioning units as a water source is also becoming more popular in large urban areas.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] As of November 2019, a Glasgow-based startup has helped a farmer in Scotland to establish edible salt marsh crops irrigated with seawater.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] An acre of previously marginal land has been put under cultivation to grow samphire, sea blite, and sea aster; these plants yield a higher profit than potatoes.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] The land is flood irrigated twice a day to simulate tidal flooding; the water is pumped from the sea using wind power.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] Additional benefits are soil remediation and carbon sequestration.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] Until the 1960s, there were fewer than half as many people on the planet as there are in 2024.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] People were not as wealthy as today, consumed fewer calories and ate less meat, so less water was needed to produce their food.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] They required a third of the volume of water humans presently take from rivers.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] Today, the competition for water resources is much more intense, because there are now more than seven billion people on the planet, increasing the likelihood of overconsumption of food produced by water-thirsty animal agriculture and intensive farming practices.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] This creates increasing competition for water from industry, urbanisation, and biofuel crops.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] Farmers will have to strive to increase productivity to meet growing demands for food, while industry and cities find ways to use water more efficiently.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] Successful agriculture depends on farmers having adequate access to water.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] However, water scarcity is already a critical constraint to farming in many parts of the world.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] There are several methods of irrigation.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] They vary in how the water is supplied to the plants.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] The goal is to apply the water to the plants as uniformly as possible, so that each plant has the amount of water it needs, neither too much nor too little.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] Irrigation can also be understood whether it is *supplementary* to rainfall, as happens in many parts of the world, or whether it is '*full* irrigation, whereby crops rarely depend on any contribution from rainfall.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] Full irrigation is less common and occurs only in arid landscapes with very low rainfall or when crops are grown in semi-arid areas outside rainy seasons.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] In *surface* (*furrow,* *flood*, or *level basin*) irrigation systems, water moves across the surface of agricultural lands to wet it and infiltrate into the soil.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] Water moves by following gravity or the slope of the land.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] Surface irrigation can be subdivided into furrow, border strip, or basin irrigation.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] It is often called *flood irrigation* when irrigation results in flooding or near-flooding of the cultivated land.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] Historically, surface irrigation has been the most common method for irrigating agricultural land in most parts of the world.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] The water application efficiency of surface irrigation is typically lower than that of other irrigation methods, due in part to limited control over applied depths.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] Surface irrigation involves significantly lower capital costs and energy requirements than pressurized irrigation systems.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] Hence, it is often the irrigation choice for developing nations, for low-value crops, and for large fields.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] Where water levels from the irrigation source permit, they are controlled by dikes (levees), usually plugged with soil.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] This is often seen in terraced rice fields (rice paddies), where the method is used to flood or control water levels in each distinct field.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] In some cases, the water is pumped or lifted by human or animal power to the level of the land.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] Surface irrigation is even used to water urban gardens in certain areas, for example, in and around Phoenix, Arizona.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] The irrigated area is surrounded by a berm and the water is delivered according to a schedule set by a local irrigation district.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] A special form of irrigation using surface water is spate irrigation, also called floodwater harvesting.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] In the event of a flood (spate), water is diverted into normally dry river beds (wadis) via a network of dams, gates, and channels and spread over large areas.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] The moisture stored in the soil will be used to grow crops thereafter.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] Spate irrigation areas are particularly located in semi-arid or arid mountainous regions.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] Drip irrigation, also known as microirrigation or trickle irrigation, functions as its name suggests.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] In this system, water is delivered at or near the root zone of plants, one drop at a time.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] This method can be the most water-efficient method of irrigation, if managed properly; evaporation and runoff are minimized.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] The field water efficiency of drip irrigation is typically in the range of 80 to 90% when managed correctly.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] In modern agriculture, drip irrigation is often combined with plastic mulch, further reducing evaporation, and is also the means of delivery of fertilizer.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] Deep percolation, where water moves below the root zone, can occur if a drip system is operated for too long or if the delivery rate is too high.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] Drip irrigation methods range from very high-tech and computerized to low-tech and labour-intensive.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] Lower water pressures are usually needed than for most other types of systems, except for low-energy center pivot systems and surface irrigation systems.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] The system can be designed for uniformity throughout a field or for precise water delivery to individual plants in a landscape containing a mix of plant species.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] Although it is difficult to regulate pressure on steep slopes, pressure-compensating emitters are available, so the field does not need to be level.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] High-tech solutions involve precisely calibrated emitters positioned along lines of tubing extending from a computerized set of valves.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] In *sprinkler* or overhead irrigation, water is piped to one or more central locations within the field and distributed by overhead high-pressure sprinklers or guns.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] A system using sprinklers, sprays, or guns mounted overhead on permanently installed risers is often referred to as a *solid-set* irrigation system.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] Higher-pressure sprinklers that rotate are called *rotors* and are driven by a ball drive, gear drive, or impact mechanism.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] Rotors can be designed to rotate in a full or partial circle.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] Guns are similar to rotors, except that they generally operate at very high pressures of 275 to 900 kPa (39.9 to 130.5 psi) and flows of 3 to 76 L/s (50 to 1200 US gal/min), usually with nozzle diameters in the range of 10 to 50 mm (0.39 to 1.97 in).
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] Guns are used not only for irrigation, but also for industrial applications such as dust suppression and logging.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] Sprinklers can also be mounted on moving platforms connected to the water source by a hose.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] Automatically moving wheeled systems known as *traveling sprinklers* may irrigate areas such as small farms, sports fields, parks, pastures, and cemeteries unattended.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] Most of these use a length of polyethylene tubing wound on a steel drum.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] As the tubing is wound onto the drum, powered by irrigation water or a small gas engine, the sprinkler is pulled across the field.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] When the sprinkler returns to the reel, the system shuts off.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] This type of system is known to most people as a "water reel" travelling irrigation sprinkler, and it is used extensively for dust suppression, irrigation, and the land application of wastewater.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] Other travellers use a flat rubber hose dragged along behind them, while a cable pulls the sprinkler platform.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] Center pivot irrigation is a form of sprinkler irrigation utilising several segments of pipe (usually galvanized steel or aluminium) joined and supported by trusses, mounted on wheeled towers with sprinklers positioned along its length.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] The system moves in a circular pattern and is fed with water from the pivot point at the center of the arc.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] These systems are found and used in all parts of the world and allow irrigation of all types of terrain.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] Newer systems have drop sprinkler heads.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] As of 2017, most center pivot systems have drops hanging from a U-shaped pipe attached at the top of the pipe with sprinkler heads that are positioned a few feet (at most) above the crop, thus limiting evaporative losses.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] Crops are often planted in a circle to conform to the center pivot.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] This type of system is known as LEPA (Low Energy Precision Application).
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] These were replaced by hydraulic systems (*T-L Irrigation*) and electric-motor-driven systems (Reinke, Valley, Zimmatic).
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] A series of pipes, each with a wheel of about 1.5 m diameter permanently affixed to its midpoint, and sprinklers along its length, is coupled together.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] Water is supplied at one end using a large hose.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] After sufficient irrigation has been applied to one strip of the field, the hose is removed, the water drained from the system, and the assembly rolled either by hand or with a purpose-built mechanism to move the sprinklers to a different position across the field.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] The process is repeated in a pattern until the whole field has been irrigated.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] This system is less expensive to install than a center pivot, but much more labor-intensive to operate – it does not travel automatically across the field: it applies water in a stationary strip, must be drained, and then rolled to a new strip.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] Most systems use 100 or 130 mm (3.9 or 5.1 in) diameter aluminum pipe.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] The pipe doubles as both a water transport and an axle for rotating all the wheels.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] A drive system (often located near the centre of the wheel line) rotates the clamped-together pipe sections as a single axle, thereby rolling the entire wheel line.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] Manual adjustment of individual wheel positions may be necessary if the system becomes misaligned.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] Wheel line systems are limited in the amount of water they can carry and limited in the height of crops that can be irrigated.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] One useful feature of a lateral move system is that it consists of sections that can be easily disconnected, allowing it to adapt to the field shape as the line is moved.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] They are most often used for small, rectilinear, or oddly-shaped fields, hilly or mountainous regions, or in regions where labor is inexpensive.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] Subirrigation has been used for many years in field crops in areas with high water tables.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] It is a method of artificially raising the water table to allow the soil to be moistened from below the plants' root zone.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] Often, those systems are located on permanent grasslands in lowlands or river valleys and combined with drainage infrastructure.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] A system of pumping stations, canals, weirs, and gates allows it to raise or lower the water level in a network of ditches, thereby controlling the water table.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] Subirrigation is also used in the commercial greenhouse production, usually for potted plants.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] Water is delivered from below, absorbed upwards, and the excess is collected for recycling.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] Typically, a solution of water and nutrients floods a container or flows through a trough for a short period (10–20 minutes) and is then pumped back into a holding tank for reuse.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] Sub-irrigation in greenhouses requires fairly sophisticated, expensive equipment and management.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] Advantages are water and nutrient conservation, and labor savings through reduced system maintenance and automation.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] It is similar in principle and action to subsurface basin irrigation.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] Another type of subirrigation is the self-watering container, also known as a sub-irrigated planter.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] This consists of a planter suspended over a reservoir with a wicking material, such as a polyester rope.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] The water is drawn up the wick through capillary action.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] A similar technique is the wicking bed; this too uses capillary action.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] Modern irrigation methods are efficient enough to supply the entire field uniformly with water, ensuring each plant receives the amount it needs, neither too much nor too little.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] Increased irrigation efficiency has several positive outcomes for the farmer, the community, and the wider environment.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] Low application efficiency indicates that the amount of water applied to the field exceeds the crop or field requirements.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] Increasing the application efficiency means that the amount of crop produced per unit of water increases.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] Improved efficiency may be achieved by applying less water to an existing field or by using water more wisely, thereby achieving higher yields in the same area of land.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] In some parts of the world, farmers are charged for irrigation water; hence, over-application has a direct financial cost to the farmer.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] Irrigation often requires pumping energy (electricity or fossil fuels) to deliver water to the field or to supply the required operating pressure.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] Hence, increased efficiency will reduce both water and energy costs per unit of agricultural production.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] A reduction in water use on one field may allow the farmer to irrigate a larger area of land, increasing total agricultural production.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] Low efficiency usually means that excess water is lost through seepage or runoff, both of which can result in loss of crop nutrients or pesticides with potential adverse impacts on the surrounding environment.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] Improving the efficiency of irrigation is usually achieved in one of two ways: either by improving the system design or by optimizing the irrigation management.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] Improving system design includes converting from one form of irrigation to another (e.g., from furrow to drip irrigation) and making small changes to the current system (e.g., adjusting flow rates and operating pressures).
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] Irrigation management refers to the scheduling of irrigation events and decisions about how much water to apply.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] Domestic gardens and landscaped areas around public buildings are often equipped with some form of irrigation in dry climates.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] In Australia, small garden sprinklers attached to a hose became a common form of irrigation, often regulated by a timer.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] In the 1960s, Hugall & Hoile, a small company in Perth, Western Australia, invented a system which they called "reticulation", by which a garden's irrigation system was divided into segments, with solenoids (electronic valves) connected to a mechanical timer.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] The system became highly popular, and within 20 years, around half of all homes in Perth had automated sprinkler systems.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] Robert Hugall made a name for himself as "the father of backyard irrigation", while former Australian cricketer Wally Edwards (who founded Holman Industries in 1966) later targeted the DIY market in garden watering systems in the early 1990s; both men grew rich from their companies.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] As climate change is causing hotter, drier weather on both sides of the continent, newer drip irrigation systems that use less water have been developed.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] In addition, desalination plants have been built or recommissioned in Perth, Sydney, Melbourne, Adelaide, and Brisbane, to meet the growing need for more water to keep plants and, especially, the tree canopy, growing.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] Negative impacts frequently accompany extensive irrigation.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] Some projects that diverted surface water for irrigation dried up the water sources, which led to a more extreme regional climate.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] Projects that relied on groundwater and pumped too much from underground aquifers created subsidence and salinization.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] Salinization of irrigation water, in turn, damaged the crops and seeped into drinking water.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] Pests and pathogens also thrived in the irrigation canals or ponds full of still water, which created regional outbreaks of diseases like malaria and schistosomiasis.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] Governments also used irrigation schemes to encourage migration, especially of more desirable populations into an area.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] Additionally, some of these large nationwide schemes failed to pay off at all, costing more than any benefit gained from increased crop yields.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] Overdrafting (depletion) of underground aquifers: In the mid-20th century, the advent of diesel and electric motors led to systems that could pump groundwater out of major aquifers faster than drainage basins could refill them.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] This can lead to permanent loss of aquifer capacity, decreased water quality, ground subsidence, and other problems.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] The future of food production in such areas as the North China Plain, the Punjab region in India and Pakistan, and the Great Plains of the US is threatened by this phenomenon.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p01] Irrigation schemes involve addressing numerous engineering and economic challenges while minimizing adverse environmental impacts.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p02] Archaeological investigations have found evidence of irrigation in areas lacking sufficient natural rainfall to support rainfed agriculture.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p02] Some of the earliest known use of the technology dates to the 6th millennium BCE in Khuzistan in the south-west of Iran.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p02] The site of Choga Mami, in present-day Iraq on the border with Iran, is believed to be the earliest to show the first canal irrigation in operation at about 6000 BCE.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p02] Irrigation was used to manipulate water in the alluvial plains of the Indus Valley Civilization, with its application estimated to have begun around 4500 BCE and to have drastically increased the size and prosperity of their agricultural settlements.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p02] The Indus Valley Civilization developed sophisticated irrigation and water-storage systems, including artificial reservoirs at Girnar dated to 3000 BCE, and an early canal irrigation system from c.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p02] Large-scale agriculture was practiced, with an extensive network of canals used for irrigation.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p02] Farmers in the Mesopotamian plain used irrigation from at least the third millennium BCE.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p02] They developed *perennial irrigation*, regularly watering crops throughout the growing season by coaxing water through a matrix of small channels formed in the field.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p02] Ancient Egyptians practiced *basin irrigation* using the flooding of the Nile to inundate land plots which had been surrounded by dikes.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p02] The flood water remained until the fertile sediment had settled before the engineers returned the surplus to the watercourse.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p02] There is evidence of the ancient Egyptian pharaoh Amenemhet III in the twelfth dynasty (about 1800 BCE) using the natural lake of the Faiyum Oasis as a reservoir to store surpluses of water for use during dry seasons.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p02] The lake swelled annually from the flooding of the Nile.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p02] The Ancient Nubians developed a form of irrigation by using a waterwheel-like device called a *sakia*.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p02] Irrigation began in Nubia between the third and second millennia BCE.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p02] It largely depended upon the flood waters that would flow through the Nile River and other rivers in what is now the Sudan.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p02] In sub-Saharan Africa, irrigation reached the Niger River region cultures and civilizations by the first or second millennium BCE and was based on wet-season flooding and water harvesting.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p02] Evidence of *terrace irrigation* occurs in pre-Columbian America, early Syria, India, and China.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p02] In the Zana Valley of the Andes Mountains in Peru, archaeologists have found remains of three irrigation canals radiocarbon-dated from the 4th millennium BCE, the 3rd millennium BCE and the 9th century CE.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p02] These canals provide the earliest record of irrigation in the New World.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p02] Traces of a canal possibly dating from the 5th millennium BCE were found under the 4th-millennium canal.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p02] Ancient Persia (modern-day Iran) used irrigation as early as the 6th millennium BCE to grow barley in areas with insufficient rainfall.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p02] The Qanats, developed in ancient Persia about 800 BCE, are among the oldest known irrigation methods still in use today.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p02] They are now found in Asia, the Middle East, and North Africa.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p02] The system comprises a network of vertical wells and gently sloping tunnels driven into the sides of cliffs and steep hills to tap groundwater.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p02] The noria, a water wheel with clay pots around the rim powered by the flow of the stream (or by animals where the water source was still), first came into use at about this time among Roman settlers in North Africa.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p02] By 150 BCE, the pots were fitted with valves to allow smoother filling as they were forced underwater.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p02] The irrigation works of ancient Sri Lanka, the earliest dating from about 300 BCE in the reign of King Pandukabhaya, and under continuous development for the next thousand years, were one of the most complex irrigation systems of the ancient world.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p02] They included underground canals and artificial reservoirs to store water.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p02] These reservoirs and canal systems were used primarily to irrigate paddy fields, which require a lot of water to cultivate.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p02] Most of these irrigation systems still exist undamaged to this day in Anuradhapura and Polonnaruwa, thanks to their advanced and precise engineering.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p02] The system was extensively restored and further extended during the reign of King Parakrama Bahu (1153–1186 CE).
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p02] The oldest known hydraulic engineers of China were Sunshu Ao (6th century BCE) of the Spring and Autumn period and Ximen Bao (5th century BCE) of the Warring States period, both of whom worked on large irrigation projects.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p02] In the Sichuan region belonging to the state of Qin of ancient China, the Dujiangyan Irrigation System devised by the Qin Chinese hydrologist and irrigation engineer Li Bing was built in 256 BCE to irrigate a vast area of farmland that today still supplies water.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p02] By the 2nd century CE, during the Han dynasty, the Chinese also used chain pumps which lifted water from a lower elevation to a higher one.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p02] These were powered by manual foot-pedal, hydraulic waterwheels, or rotating mechanical wheels pulled by oxen.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p02] The water was used for public works, providing water for urban residential quarters and palace gardens, but mostly for irrigation of farmland canals and channels in the fields.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p02] Korea, Chang Yŏngsil, also known as Jang Yeong-sil, a Korean engineer of the Joseon dynasty, under the active direction of the king, Sejong the Great, invented the world's first rain gauge, *uryanggye* (Korean: 우량계) in 1441.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p02] It was installed in irrigation tanks as part of a nationwide system to measure and collect rainfall for agricultural applications.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p02] Planners and farmers could better use the information gathered in the survey with this instrument.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p02] The earliest agricultural irrigation canal system known in the area of the present-day United States dates to between 1200 BCE and 800 BCE and was discovered by Desert Archaeology, Inc. in Marana, Arizona (adjacent to Tucson) in 2009.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p02] The irrigation-canal system predates the Hohokam culture by two thousand years and belongs to an unidentified culture.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p02] In North America, the Hohokam were the only culture known to rely on irrigation canals to water their crops, and their irrigation systems supported the largest population in the Southwest by CE 1300.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p02] The Hohokam constructed simple canals, combined with weirs, for their agricultural pursuits.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p02] Between the 7th and 14th centuries, they built and maintained extensive irrigation networks along the lower Salt and middle Gila Rivers that rivaled the complexity of those used in the ancient Near East, Egypt, and China.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p02] These were constructed using relatively simple excavation tools, without the benefit of advanced engineering technologies, and achieved drops of a few feet per mile, balancing erosion and siltation.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p02] The Hohokam cultivated cotton, tobacco, maize, beans, and squash varieties and harvested an assortment of wild plants.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p02] Late in the Hohokam Chronological Sequence, they used extensive dry-farming systems, primarily to grow agave for food and fiber.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p02] Their reliance on agricultural strategies based on canal irrigation, vital in their less-than-hospitable desert environment and arid climate, provided the basis for the aggregation of rural populations into stable urban centers.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p02] The oldest known irrigation canals in the Americas are in the desert of northern Peru in the Zaña Valley near the hamlet of Nanchoc.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p02] The canals have been radiocarbon dated to at least 3400 BCE and possibly as old as 4700 BCE.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p02] The canals at that time irrigated crops such as peanuts, squash, manioc, chenopods, a relative of Quinoa, and later maize.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p02] The scale of global irrigation increased dramatically over the 20th century.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p02] In 1800, 8 million hectares were irrigated; in 1950, 94 million hectares, and in 1990, 235 million hectares.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p02] National governments led most irrigation schemes within their borders, but private investors and other nations, especially the United States, China, and European countries like the United Kingdom, funded and organized some schemes within other nations.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p02] Irrigation enabled the production of more crops, especially commodity crops in areas that otherwise could not support them.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p02] In the 20th century, global anxiety, specifically about the American cotton monopoly, fueled many empirical irrigation projects: Britain began developing irrigation in India, the Ottomans in Egypt, the French in Algeria, the Portuguese in Angola, the Germans in Togo, and Soviets in Central Asia.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p02] Some projects that diverted surface water for irrigation dried up water sources, leading to a more extreme regional climate.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p02] Salinization of irrigation water damaged the crops and seeped into drinking water.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p02] Irrigated land in the United States increased from 300,000 acres in 1880 to 4.1 million in 1890 to 7.3 million in 1900.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p02] Two thirds of this irrigation sources from groundwater or small ponds and reservoirs, while the other one third comes from large dams.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p02] One of the main attractions of irrigation in the West was its increased dependability compared to rainfall-watered agriculture in the East.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p02] Proponents argued that farmers with a dependable water supply could more easily get loans from bankers interested in this more predictable farming model.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p02] Most irrigation in the Great Plains region derived from underground aquifers.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p02] Euro-American farmers who colonized the region in the 19th century tried to grow the commodity crops they were used to, such as wheat, corn, and alfalfa, but rainfall limited their yields.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p02] Between the late 1800s and the 1930s, farmers used wind-powered pumps to draw groundwater.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p02] These windpumps had limited power, but the development of gas-powered pumps in the mid-1930s pushed wells deep into the Ogallala Aquifer.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p02] Farmers irrigated fields by laying pipes across the field with sprinklers at intervals, a labor-intensive process, until the advent of the center-pivot sprinkler after World War II, which made irrigation significantly easier.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p02] By the 1970s, farmers drained the aquifer ten times faster than it could recharge, and by 1993, they had removed half of the accessible water.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p02] Large-scale federal funding and intervention pushed through the majority of irrigation projects in the West, especially in California, Colorado, Arizona, and Nevada.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p02] At first, plans to increase irrigated farmland, largely by giving land to farmers and asking them to find water, failed across the board.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p02] Congress passed the Desert Land Act in 1877 and the Carey Act in 1894, which only marginally increased irrigation.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p02] Only in 1902 did Congress pass the National Reclamation Act, which channeled money from the sale of western public lands, in parcels up to 160 acres large, into irrigation projects on public or private land in the arid West.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p02] The Congressmen who passed the law and their wealthy supporters supported Western irrigation because it would increase American exports, 'reclaim' the West, and push the Eastern poor out West for a better life.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p02] While the National Reclamation Act was the most successful piece of federal irrigation legislation, its implementation did not go as planned.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p02] The Reclamation Service chose to push most of the Act's money toward construction rather than settlement, so the Service overwhelmingly prioritized building large dams like the Hoover Dam.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p02] Over the 20th century, Congress and state governments grew more frustrated with the Reclamation Service and the irrigation schemes.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p02] Frederick Newell, head of the Reclamation Service, proving uncompromising and challenging to work with, falling crop prices, resistance to delay debt payments, and refusal to begin new projects until the completion of old ones all contributed.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p02] The Reclamation Extension Act of 1914, transferring a significant amount of irrigation decision-making power regarding irrigation projects from the Reclamation Service to Congress, was in many ways a result of increasing political unpopularity of the Reclamation Service.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p02] In the lower Colorado Basin of Arizona, Colorado, and Nevada, the states derive irrigation water largely from rivers, especially the Colorado River, which irrigates more than 4.5 million acres of land, with a less significant amount coming from groundwater.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p02] California, Arizona sued California for increased access to the Colorado River, under the grounds that their groundwater supply could not sustain their almost entirely irrigation-based agricultural economy, which they won.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p02] California, which began irrigating in earnest in the 1870s in San Joaquin Valley, had passed the Wright Act of 1887 permitting agricultural communities to construct and operate needed irrigation works.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p02] The Colorado River also irrigates large fields in California's Imperial Valley, fed by the National Reclamation Act-built All-American Canal.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p02] When the Bolsheviks conquered Central Asia in 1917, the native Kazakhs, Uzbeks, and Turkmens used minimal irrigation.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p02] The Slavic immigrants pushed into the area by the Tsarist government brought their irrigation methods, including waterwheels, the use of rice paddies to restore salted land, and underground irrigation channels.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p02] Russians dismissed these techniques as crude and inefficient.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p02] Despite this, tsarist officials maintained these systems through the late 19th century without other solutions.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p02] Before conquering the area, the Russian government accepted a 1911 American proposal to send hydraulic experts to Central Asia to investigate the potential for large-scale irrigation.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p02] A 1918 decree by Lenin then encouraged irrigation development in the region, which began in the 1930s.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p02] When it did, Stalin and other Soviet leaders prioritized large-scale, ambitious hydraulic projects, especially along the Volga River.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p02] The Soviet irrigation push stemmed mainly from their late 19th century fears of the American cotton monopoly and subsequent desire to achieve cotton self-sufficiency.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p02] They had built up their textile manufacturing industry in the 19th century, requiring increased cotton and irrigation, as the region did not receive enough rainfall to support cotton farming.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p02] The Russians built dams on the Don and Kuban Rivers for irrigation, removing freshwater flow from the Sea of Azov and making it much saltier.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p02] Depletion and salinization scourged other areas of the Russian irrigation project.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p02] In the 1950s, Soviet officials began also diverting the Syr Darya and the Amu Darya, which fed the Aral Sea.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p02] Before diversion, the rivers delivered 55 cubic kilometres (13 cu mi) of water to the Aral Sea per year, but after diversion, they delivered only 6 cubic kilometres (1.4 cu mi).
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p02] Because of its reduced inflow, the Aral Sea covered less than half of its original seabed, which made the regional climate more extreme and created airborne salinization, lowering nearby crop yields.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p02] By 1975, the USSR used eight times as much water as it had in 1913, mostly for irrigation.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p02] Russia's expansion of irrigation began to decline in the late 1980s, and irrigated hectares in Central Asia peaked at 7 million.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p02] Mikhail Gorbachev killed a proposed plan to reverse the Ob and Yenisei for irrigation in 1986, and the breakup of the USSR in 1991 ended Russian investment in Central Asian cotton irrigation.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p02] Various irrigation schemes with different goals and success rates were implemented across Africa in the 20th century, but were all influenced by colonial forces.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p02] The Tana River Irrigation Scheme in eastern Kenya, completed between 1948 and 1963, opened up new lands for agriculture.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p02] The Kenyan government attempted to resettle the area with detainees from the Mau Mau uprising.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p02] Italian oil drillers discovered Libya's underground water resources during the Italian colonization of Libya.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p02] This water lay dormant until 1969, when Muammar al-Gaddafi and American Armand Hammer built the Great Man-Made River to deliver the Saharan water to the coast.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p02] The water largely contributed to irrigation but cost four to ten times more than the crops it produced were worth.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p02] In 1912, the Union of South Africa established an irrigation department and began investing in water storage infrastructure and irrigation systems.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p02] The government used irrigation and dam-building to further social goals such as poverty relief by creating construction jobs for poor whites and by developing irrigation schemes to increase white farming.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p02] One of their first significant irrigation projects was the Hartbeespoort Dam, begun in 1916 to elevate the living conditions of the 'poor whites' in the region and eventually completed as a 'whites only' employment opportunity.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p02] The Pretoria irrigation scheme, Kammanassie project, and Buchuberg irrigation scheme on the Orange River all followed in the same vein in the 1920s and 30s.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p02] In Egypt, modern irrigation began with Muhammad Ali Pasha in the mid-1800s, who sought to achieve Egyptian independence from the Ottomans through increased trade with Europe—specifically cotton exportation.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p02] His administration proposed replacing the traditional Nile basin irrigation, which took advantage of the annual ebb and flow of the Nile, with irrigation barrages in the lower Nile, which better suited cotton production.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p02] Egypt devoted 105,000 ha to cotton in 1861, a figure that increased fivefold by 1865.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p02] Most of their exports were shipped to England, and the United States Civil War-induced cotton scarcity in the 1860s cemented Egypt as England's cotton producer.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p02] As the Egyptian economy became more dependent on cotton in the 20th century, controlling even small Nile floods became more important.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p02] Cotton production was more at risk of destruction than more common crops like barley or wheat.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p02] After the British occupation of Egypt in 1882, the British intensified the conversion to perennial irrigation with the construction of the Delta Barrage, the Assiut Barrage, and the first Aswan Dam.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-p02] Perennial irrigation decreased local control over water and made traditional subsistence farming or the farming of other crops incredibly difficult, eventually contributing to widespread peasant bankruptcy and the 1879-1882 'Urabi revolt.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-scheduling] Modern scheduling has evolved from simple calendar-based timers to "smart" systems that adapt dynamically to weather conditions and soil moisture levels.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-scheduling] Irrigation scheduling can be grouped into three primary methodologies, ranging from observation to advanced data analytics.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-scheduling] The most basic form of scheduling relies on visual cues or physical inspection.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-scheduling] This method uses sensors placed directly in the root zone to measure the volumetric water content or soil water tension.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-scheduling] These sensors can act as a "thermostat" for irrigation, triggering the system only when moisture drops below a specific Management Allowed Depletion (MAD) threshold.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-scheduling] Also known as the "Checkbook Method," this approach calculates the water balance of the soil.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-scheduling] This method relies heavily on accurate weather data to calculate daily water loss.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-scheduling] Advancements in "weather awareness" have led to the development of smart irrigation controllers that automate the scheduling process.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-scheduling] Evapotranspiration (ET) controllers adjust irrigation schedules daily based on local weather conditions.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-scheduling] They calculate the Reference Evapotranspiration ( $ET_{0}$ )—the amount of water a standard grass surface would lose given the current temperature, humidity, wind speed, and solar radiation.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-scheduling] Instead of predicting water loss via weather data, these controllers measure actual soil moisture.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-scheduling] Successful scheduling requires understanding specific crop needs.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-scheduling] Not all plants use water at the same rate.
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-scheduling] The "weather awareness" ( $ET_{0}$ ) must be modified by a Crop Coefficient ( $K_{c}$ ) to get the actual water requirement ( $ET_{c}$ ).
[src:irrigation-automation/irrigation-scheduling] MAD is the percentage of available soil water that can be depleted before plant stress occurs.
[src:irrigation-automation/soil-moisture] Water that enters a field is removed from it by runoff, drainage, evaporation or transpiration.
[src:irrigation-automation/soil-moisture] Water affects soil formation, structure, stability and erosion but is of primary concern with respect to plant growth.
[src:irrigation-automation/soil-moisture] It is the solvent in which nutrients are carried to, into and throughout the plant.
[src:irrigation-automation/soil-moisture] It provides the turgidity by which the plant keeps itself in proper position.
[src:irrigation-automation/soil-moisture] In addition, water alters the soil profile by dissolving and re-depositing mineral and organic solutes and colloids, often at lower levels, a process called leaching.
[src:irrigation-automation/soil-moisture] In a loam soil, solids constitute half the volume, gas one-quarter of the volume, and water one-quarter of the volume of which only half will be available to most plants, with a strong variation according to matric potential.
[src:irrigation-automation/soil-moisture] Water moves in soil under the influence of gravity, osmosis and capillarity.
[src:irrigation-automation/soil-moisture] When water enters the soil, it displaces air from interconnected macropores by buoyancy, and breaks aggregates into which air is entrapped, a process called slaking.
[src:irrigation-automation/soil-moisture] The rate at which a soil can absorb water depends on the soil and its other conditions.
[src:irrigation-automation/soil-moisture] As a plant grows, its roots remove water from the largest pores (macropores) first.
[src:irrigation-automation/soil-moisture] Soon the larger pores hold only air, and the remaining water is found only in the intermediate- and smallest-sized pores (micropores).
[src:irrigation-automation/soil-moisture] The water in the smallest pores is so strongly held to particle surfaces that plant roots cannot pull it away.
[src:irrigation-automation/soil-moisture] Consequently, not all soil water is available to plants, with a strong dependence on texture.
[src:irrigation-automation/soil-moisture] When saturated, the soil may lose nutrients as the water drains.
[src:irrigation-automation/soil-moisture] Water moves in a draining field under the influence of pressure where the soil is locally saturated and by capillarity pull to drier parts of the soil.
[src:irrigation-automation/soil-moisture] Most plant water needs are supplied from the suction caused by evaporation from plant leaves (transpiration) and a lower fraction is supplied by suction created by osmotic pressure differences between the plant interior and the soil solution.
[src:irrigation-automation/soil-moisture] Plant roots must seek out water and grow preferentially in moister soil microsites, but some parts of the root system are also able to remoisten dry parts of the soil.
[src:irrigation-automation/soil-moisture] Insufficient water will damage the yield of a crop.
[src:irrigation-automation/soil-moisture] Most of the available water is used in transpiration to pull nutrients into the plant.
[src:irrigation-automation/soil-moisture] Soil water is also important for climate modeling and numerical weather prediction.
[src:irrigation-automation/soil-moisture] The Global Climate Observing System specified soil water as one of the 50 Essential Climate Variables (ECVs).
[src:irrigation-automation/soil-moisture] Soil water can be measured in situ with soil moisture sensors or can be estimated at various scales and resolution: from local or wifi measures via sensors in the soil to satellite imagery that combines data capture and hydrological models.
[src:irrigation-automation/soil-moisture] Each method exhibits pros and cons, and hence, the integration of different techniques may decrease the drawbacks of a single given method.
[src:irrigation-automation/soil-moisture] By convention it is defined at 0.33 bar suction.
[src:irrigation-automation/soil-moisture] as the plant cannot produce sufficient suction to draw that water in.
[src:irrigation-automation/soil-moisture] is the minimum amount of water plants need to not wilt and approximates the boundary between available and unavailable water.
[src:irrigation-automation/soil-moisture] By convention it is defined as 15 bar suction.
[src:irrigation-automation/soil-moisture] plants begin to wilt and then die unless they are able to recover after water replenishment thanks to species-specific adaptations.
[src:irrigation-automation/soil-moisture] Water is retained in a soil when the adhesive force of attraction that water's hydrogen atoms have for the oxygen of soil particles is stronger than the cohesive forces that water's hydrogen feels for water oxygen atoms.
[src:irrigation-automation/soil-moisture] When a field is flooded, the soil pore space is completely filled by water.
[src:irrigation-automation/soil-moisture] The field will drain under the force of gravity until it reaches what is called field capacity, at which point the smallest pores are filled with water and the largest with water and gases.
[src:irrigation-automation/soil-moisture] The total amount of water held when field capacity is reached is a function of the specific surface area of the soil particles.
[src:irrigation-automation/soil-moisture] As a result, high clay and high organic soils have higher field capacities.
[src:irrigation-automation/soil-moisture] The potential energy of water per unit volume relative to pure water in reference conditions is called water potential.
[src:irrigation-automation/soil-moisture] Total water potential is a sum of matric potential which results from capillary action, osmotic potential for saline soil, and gravitational potential when dealing with downward water movement.
[src:irrigation-automation/soil-moisture] Water potential in soil usually has negative values, and therefore it is also expressed in suction, which is defined as the minus of water potential.
[src:irrigation-automation/soil-moisture] Suction has a positive value and can be regarded as the total force required to pull or push water out of soil.
[src:irrigation-automation/soil-moisture] Water potential or suction is expressed in units of kPa (103 pascal), bar (100 kPa), or cm H2O (approximately 0.098 kPa).
[src:irrigation-automation/soil-moisture] Common logarithm of suction in cm H2O is called pF.
[src:irrigation-automation/soil-moisture] The forces with which water is held in soils determine its availability to plants.
[src:irrigation-automation/soil-moisture] Forces of adhesion hold water strongly to mineral and humus surfaces and less strongly to itself by cohesive forces.
[src:irrigation-automation/soil-moisture] A plant's root may penetrate a very small volume of water that is adhering to soil and be initially able to draw in water that is only lightly held by the cohesive forces.
[src:irrigation-automation/soil-moisture] But as the droplet is drawn down, the forces of adhesion of the water for the soil particles produce increasingly higher suction, finally up to 1500 kPa (pF = 4.2).
[src:irrigation-automation/soil-moisture] At 1500 kPa suction, the soil water amount is called wilting point.
[src:irrigation-automation/soil-moisture] The next level, called air-dry, occurs at 100,000 kPa suction (pF = 6).
[src:irrigation-automation/soil-moisture] Finally the oven dry condition is reached at 1,000,000 kPa suction (pF = 7).
[src:irrigation-automation/soil-moisture] All water below wilting point is called unavailable water.
[src:irrigation-automation/soil-moisture] When the soil moisture content is optimal for plant growth, the water in the large (macropores) and intermediate (mesopores) size pores can move about in the soil and be easily used by plants.
[src:irrigation-automation/soil-moisture] The amount of water remaining in a soil drained to field capacity and the amount that is available are functions of the soil texture.
[src:irrigation-automation/soil-moisture] Sandy soil will retain very little water, while clay will hold the maximum amount.
[src:irrigation-automation/soil-moisture] The available water for the silt loam might be 20% whereas for the sand it might be only 6% by volume, as shown in this table.
[src:irrigation-automation/soil-moisture] The above are average values for the soil textures.
[src:irrigation-automation/soil-moisture] Water moves through soil due to the forces of gravity, osmosis and capillarity.
[src:irrigation-automation/soil-moisture] At 0 to 33 kPa suction (field capacity), water is pushed through soil from the point of its application under the force of gravity and the pressure gradient created by differences in the pressure of water; this is called saturated flow.
[src:irrigation-automation/soil-moisture] At higher suction, water movement is pulled by capillarity from wetter toward drier soil.
[src:irrigation-automation/soil-moisture] This is caused by water's adhesion to soil solids, and is called unsaturated flow.
[src:irrigation-automation/soil-moisture] Fine-textured soils with granular structure are most favourable to infiltration of water.
[src:irrigation-automation/soil-moisture] Coarse matter is best and if on the surface helps prevent the destruction of soil structure and the creation of soil crusts.
[src:irrigation-automation/soil-moisture] Warm soils take in water faster while frozen soils such as permafrost may not be able to absorb depending on the type of freezing.
[src:irrigation-automation/soil-moisture] Water infiltration rates range from 0.25 cm per hour for high clay soils to 2.5 cm per hour for sand and well stabilized and aggregated soil structures.
[src:irrigation-automation/soil-moisture] Water flows through the ground unevenly, in the form of so-called *gravity fingers*, because of the surface tension between water particles.
[src:irrigation-automation/soil-moisture] Tree roots, whether living or dead, create preferential channels for rainwater flow through soil, magnifying infiltration rates of water up to 27 times.
[src:irrigation-automation/soil-moisture] Flooding temporarily increases soil permeability in river beds, helping to recharge aquifers.
[src:irrigation-automation/soil-moisture] Water applied to a soil is pushed by pressure gradients from the point of its application where it is saturated locally, to less saturated areas, such as the vadose zone.
[src:irrigation-automation/soil-moisture] Water that drains through the soil at macropores when it rains is called gravitational water.
[src:irrigation-automation/soil-moisture] In the United States percolation water due to rainfall ranges from almost zero centimeters just east of the Rocky Mountains to fifty or more centimeters per day in the Appalachian Mountains and the north coast of the Gulf of Mexico.
[src:irrigation-automation/soil-moisture] Water is pulled by capillary action due to the adhesion force of water to the soil solids, producing a suction gradient from wet towards drier soil and from macropores to micropores.
[src:irrigation-automation/soil-moisture] The so-called Richards equation allows calculation of the time rate of change of moisture content in soils due to the movement of water in unsaturated soils.
[src:irrigation-automation/soil-moisture] Interestingly, this equation attributed to Lorenzo Richards was originally published by Lewis Richardson in 1922.
[src:irrigation-automation/soil-moisture] The soil moisture velocity equation, which can be solved using the finite water-content vadose zone flow method, describes the velocity of flowing water through an unsaturated soil in the vertical direction.
[src:irrigation-automation/soil-moisture] Preferential flow occurs along interconnected macropores, crevices, root and worm channels, which drain water under gravity.
[src:irrigation-automation/soil-moisture] Many models based on soil physics now allow for some representation of preferential flow as a dual continuum, dual porosity or dual permeability options, but these have generally been "bolted on" to the Richards solution without any rigorous physical underpinning.
[src:irrigation-automation/soil-moisture] Of equal importance to the storage and movement of water in soil is the means by which plants acquire it and their nutrients.
[src:irrigation-automation/soil-moisture] Most soil water is taken up by plants as passive absorption caused by the pulling force of water evaporating (transpiring) from the long column of water (xylem sap flow) that leads from the plant's roots to its leaves, according to the cohesion-tension theory.
[src:irrigation-automation/soil-moisture] The upward movement of water and solutes (hydraulic lift) is regulated in the roots by the endodermis and in the plant foliage by stomatal conductance, and can be interrupted in root and shoot xylem vessels by cavitation, also called *xylem embolism*.
[src:irrigation-automation/soil-moisture] In addition, the high concentration of salts within plant roots creates an osmotic pressure gradient that pushes soil water into the roots.
[src:irrigation-automation/soil-moisture] Osmotic absorption becomes more important during times of low water transpiration caused by lower temperatures (for example at night) or high humidity, and the reverse occurs under high temperature or low humidity.
[src:irrigation-automation/soil-moisture] It is these processes that cause guttation and wilting, respectively.
[src:irrigation-automation/soil-moisture] Root extension is vital for plant survival.
[src:irrigation-automation/soil-moisture] The total surface area of the loam soil was estimated to be 52,000 square meters.
[src:irrigation-automation/soil-moisture] In other words, the roots were in contact with only 1.2% of the soil volume.
[src:irrigation-automation/soil-moisture] However, root extension should be viewed as a dynamic process, allowing new roots to explore a new volume of soil each day, increasing dramatically the total volume of soil explored over a given growth period, and thus the volume of water taken up by the root system over this period.
[src:irrigation-automation/soil-moisture] Root architecture, i.e. the spatial configuration of the root system, plays a prominent role in the adaptation of plants to soil water and nutrient availability, and thus in plant productivity.
[src:irrigation-automation/soil-moisture] Roots must seek out water as the unsaturated flow of water in soil can move only at a rate of up to 2.5 cm per day; as a result they are constantly dying and growing as they seek out high concentrations of soil moisture.
[src:irrigation-automation/soil-moisture] Insufficient soil moisture, to the point of causing wilting, will cause permanent damage and crop yields will suffer.
[src:irrigation-automation/soil-moisture] When grain sorghum was exposed to soil suction as low as 1300 kPa during the seed head emergence through bloom and seed set stages of growth, its production was reduced by 34%.
[src:irrigation-automation/soil-moisture] Only a small fraction (0.1% to 1%) of the water used by a plant is held within the plant.
[src:irrigation-automation/soil-moisture] The majority is ultimately lost via transpiration.
[src:irrigation-automation/soil-moisture] At the same time evaporation from the soil surface is also substantial, the transpiration:evaporation ratio (T/ET) varying according to vegetation type and climate, peaking in tropical rainforests and dipping in steppes and deserts.
[src:irrigation-automation/soil-moisture] Transpiration plus evaporative soil moisture loss is called evapotranspiration.
[src:irrigation-automation/soil-moisture] Evapotranspiration plus water held in the plant totals to consumptive use, which is nearly identical to evapotranspiration.
[src:irrigation-automation/soil-moisture] The total water used in an agricultural field includes surface runoff, drainage and consumptive use.
[src:irrigation-automation/soil-moisture] The use of loose mulches will reduce evaporative losses for a period after a field is irrigated, but in the end, the total evaporative loss (plant plus soil) will approach that of uncovered soil, while more water is immediately available for plant growth.
[src:irrigation-automation/soil-moisture] Water use efficiency is measured by the transpiration ratio, which is the ratio of the total water transpired by a plant to the dry weight of the harvested plant.
[src:irrigation-automation/soil-moisture] Transpiration ratios for crops range from 300 to 700.
[src:irrigation-automation/soil-moisture] For example, alfalfa may have a transpiration ratio of 500; as a result, 500 kilograms of water will produce one kilogram of dry alfalfa.
